on of shamanism into archaeology theory, where a male sorcerer emerged as the key agent of prehistoric art. More recent efforts to provide a universal shamanic explanation for rock art via South Africa and neurobiology likewise gloss over historical evidence of diversity. By contrast this book argues for recognizing indeterminacy in the categories we use, and reopening them by recalling their complex history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aShamanismzRussia (Federation)zSiberia. 0aShamanszRussia (Federation)zSiberia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aanthropologists.  aarchaeologists.  aarchaeology theory.  aart and religion.  acultural anthropology.  adiverse history.  aethnographers.  aethnographic records.  aeurope.  ahistorians.  ahistorical.  ahistory of anthropology.  ahuman history.  ahumanity.  amodern perspective.  anatural historians.  aneurobiology.  anonfiction.  aprehistory.  aproto priest.  areligious figures.  aretrospective.  ashamanic practitioners.  ashamanism.  ashamans.  asocial science.  atransgendered shamans.  aworld history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027531740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095531840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520955318423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520955318/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY